<subSubSection pageId="65" pageNumber="66" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="65.[189,454,1358,1384]" box="[189,454,1358,1384]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,454,1358,1384]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,454,1358,1384]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[187,1399,1406,1543]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[189,649,1406,1432]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucozonoides" status="sp. nov." subGenus="Floccocheila">
<emphasis box="[189,301,1406,1432]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Cheilosia</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[316,468,1406,1432]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Floccocheila</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[484,649,1406,1432]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">leucozonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[655,743,1407,1433]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is a large sized species with long and dense body pilosity like most subcongeners. From all other members of the subgenus 
<emphasis box="[962,989,1443,1469]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">C.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1006,1028,1444,1469]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">F.</emphasis>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls, 2022" authorityName="Barkalov &amp; Ståhls" authorityYear="2022" box="[1052,1218,1443,1469]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Cheilosia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leucozonoides" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1052,1218,1443,1469]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">leucozonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1226,1317,1443,1469]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs by the following combination of characters: eye pilosity black, basoflagellomere blackish in colour, and presence of black pile on tergites III–IV.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[189,1302,1584,1658]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="65.[189,324,1584,1610]" box="[189,324,1584,1610]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,324,1584,1610]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,324,1584,1610]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="65.[189,1302,1632,1658]" box="[189,1302,1632,1658]" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">
The specific epithet ‘ 
<emphasis box="[436,511,1632,1658]" italics="true" pageId="65" pageNumber="66">leucos</emphasis>
’ is from the Greek, and refers to the pale wing veins of the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
